To get the positive modulo, we can use modulo(K - b, a), which returns a non-negative result. So in the Java code, perhaps they are using that 10000*a to make sure that the value is positive. So the equivalent in Fortran would be to compute (K - b) modulo a, but using the modulo function that returns a non-negative value. So in Fortran, ans can be computed as modulo(K - b, a) + b. But if K < b, then ans is K.

So the code in Java has:

ans = (int) ((10000 * a + K - b) % a + b);
if (b > K) ans = (int) K;

But why the 10000*a?
